Reasoning: The paper discusses the use of the Minimum Description Length (MDL) principle as a model selection technique for Bernoulli and multinomial distributions. This topic falls under the intersection of several computer science sub-fields, including information theory (cs.IT), machine learning (cs.LG), data structures and algorithms (cs.DS), computational complexity (cs.CC), and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper's focus on compression performance and model complexity estimation suggests a stronger emphasis on information theory and machine learning, hence the higher likelihood of cs.IT and cs.LG. However, the paper's theoretical analysis and experimental comparisons may also appeal to researchers in data structures and algorithms, computational complexity, and artificial intelligence.
